<p><a name="Literature" id="Literature"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Domain_theory&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: Literature">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Literature</span></h2>
<p>Probably one of the most recommendable books on domain theory today, giving a very clear and detailed view on many parts of the basic theory:</p>
<ul>
<li><cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFG._Gierz.2C_K._H._Hofmann.2C_K._Keimel.2C_J._D._Lawson.2C_M._Mislove.2C_and_D._S._Scott2003">G. Gierz, K. H. Hofmann, K. Keimel, J. D. Lawson, M. Mislove, and D. S. Scott (2003). "Continuous Lattices and Domains". <i>Encyclopedia of Mathematics and its Applications</i>. <b>93</b>. Cambridge University Press. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0521803381" class="internal">ISBN 0-521-80338-1</a>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Continuous+Lattices+and+Domains&amp;rft.atitle=Encyclopedia+of+Mathematics+and+its+Applications&amp;rft.aulast=G.+Gierz%2C+K.+H.+Hofmann%2C+K.+Keimel%2C+J.+D.+Lawson%2C+M.+Mislove%2C+and+D.+S.+Scott&amp;rft.au=G.+Gierz%2C+K.+H.+Hofmann%2C+K.+Keimel%2C+J.+D.+Lawson%2C+M.+Mislove%2C+and+D.+S.+Scott&amp;rft.date=2003&amp;rft.volume=93&amp;rft.pub=Cambridge+University+Press&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Domain_theory"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
</ul>
<p>A standard resource on domain theory, which is freely available online:</p>
<ul>
<li><cite style="font-style:normal"><a href="/wiki/Samson_Abramsky" title="Samson Abramsky">S. Abramsky</a>, A. Jung (1994). "<a href="http://www.cs.bham.ac.uk/~axj/pub/papers/handy1.pdf" class="external text" title="http://www.cs.bham.ac.uk/~axj/pub/papers/handy1.pdf" rel="nofollow">Domain theory</a>" (PDF). S. Abramsky, D. M. Gabbay, T. S. E. Maibaum, editors, <i>Handbook of Logic in Computer Science</i> <b>III</b>, Oxford University Press. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/019853762X" class="internal">ISBN 0-19-853762-X</a>. <span class="reference-accessdate">Retrieved on <a href="/wiki/2007" title="2007">2007</a>-<a href="/wiki/October_13" title="October 13">10-13</a></span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=proceeding&amp;rft.btitle=Handbook+of+Logic+in+Computer+Science&amp;rft.atitle=Domain+theory&amp;rft.au=%5B%5BSamson+Abramsky%7CS.+Abramsky%5D%5D%2C+A.+Jung&amp;rft.date=1994&amp;rft.pub=Oxford+University+Press&amp;rft.series=III&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.cs.bham.ac.uk%2F%7Eaxj%2Fpub%2Fpapers%2Fhandy1.pdf"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
</ul>
<p>Another online paper explains the motivation, why the notion of “topology” can be applied in the investigation of concepts of the computer science:</p>
<ul>
<li><cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFAlex_Simpson2001-2002">Alex Simpson (2001-2002). <a href="http://www.dcs.ed.ac.uk/home/als/Teaching/MSfS/l3.ps" class="external text" title="http://www.dcs.ed.ac.uk/home/als/Teaching/MSfS/l3.ps" rel="nofollow">"Part III: Topological Spaces from a Computational Perspective"</a>. <i>Mathematical Structures for Semantics</i><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.dcs.ed.ac.uk/home/als/Teaching/MSfS/l3.ps" class="external free" title="http://www.dcs.ed.ac.uk/home/als/Teaching/MSfS/l3.ps" rel="nofollow">http://www.dcs.ed.ac.uk/home/als/Teaching/MSfS/l3.ps</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2007-10-13</span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Part+III%3A+Topological+Spaces+from+a+Computational+Perspective&amp;rft.atitle=Mathematical+Structures+for+Semantics&amp;rft.aulast=Alex+Simpson&amp;rft.au=Alex+Simpson&amp;rft.date=2001-2002&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.dcs.ed.ac.uk%2Fhome%2Fals%2FTeaching%2FMSfS%2Fl3.ps&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Domain_theory"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
</ul>
<p>The “References” section of this web page provides many online materials on domain theory.</p>
<p>One of Scott's classical papers:</p>
<ul>
<li><cite style="font-style:normal" class="" id="CITEREFD._S._Scott1975"><a href="/wiki/Dana_Scott" title="Dana Scott">D. S. Scott</a> (1975). "Data types as lattices". <i>Proceedings of the International Summer Institute and Logic Colloquium, Kiel</i>, in <i>Lecture Notes in Mathematics</i> (Springer-Verlag) <b>499</b>: 579–651.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Data+types+as+lattices&amp;rft.jtitle=Proceedings+of+the+International+Summer+Institute+and+Logic+Colloquium%2C+Kiel%27%27%2C+in+%27%27Lecture+Notes+in+Mathematics&amp;rft.aulast=D.+S.+Scott&amp;rft.au=D.+S.+Scott&amp;rft.date=1975&amp;rft.volume=499&amp;rft.pages=579%E2%80%93651&amp;rft.pub=Springer-Verlag&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Domain_theory"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
</ul>
<p>A textbook treatment of domain theory with connections to lambda calculus and types:</p>
<ul>
<li><cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFCarl_A._Gunter1992">Carl A. Gunter (1992). <i>Semantics of Programming Languages</i>. MIT Press.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Semantics+of+Programming+Languages&amp;rft.aulast=Carl+A.+Gunter&amp;rft.au=Carl+A.+Gunter&amp;rft.date=1992&amp;rft.pub=MIT+Press&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Domain_theory"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
</ul>
<p>A general, easy-to-read account of order theory, including an introduction to domain theory as well:</p>
<ul>
<li><cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFB._A._Davey_and_H._A._Priestley2002">B. A. Davey and H. A. Priestley (2002). <i>Introduction to Lattices and Order</i> (2nd edition ed.). Cambridge University Press. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0521784514" class="internal">ISBN 0-521-78451-4</a>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Introduction+to+Lattices+and+Order&amp;rft.aulast=B.+A.+Davey+and+H.+A.+Priestley&amp;rft.au=B.+A.+Davey+and+H.+A.+Priestley&amp;rft.date=2002&amp;rft.edition=2nd+edition&amp;rft.pub=Cambridge+University+Press&amp;rft.isbn=0-521-78451-4&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Domain_theory"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
</ul>
<p>An account of the Laws for Actor systems and how they can be used to justify Scott's continuity criterion:</p>
<ul>
<li><cite style="font-style:normal">Carl Hewitt and Henry Baker (August 1977). "Actors and Continuous Functionals". <i>Proceedings of IFIP Working Conference on Formal Description of Programming Concepts</i>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=proceeding&amp;rft.btitle=Proceedings+of+IFIP+Working+Conference+on+Formal+Description+of+Programming+Concepts&amp;rft.atitle=Actors+and+Continuous+Functionals&amp;rft.au=Carl+Hewitt+and+Henry+Baker&amp;rft.date=1977"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
</ul>


